<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06119157 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06119157 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Mattie Belle Jones; ... Studied genealogy  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  OBITUARY; ELDERLY; WOMAN; HISTORY; FAMILY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A memorial service will be held Tuesday for Mattie Belle Jones of San Jose, aneducator, bookkeeper and granddaughter of Midwest pioneer homesteaders, whodied April 20 of a respiratory infection. She was 99.;    Mrs. Jones was bornin Nebraska and grew up on farms near North Bend. She graduated fromNebraska's Fremont Normal School, now known as Midland College, when she was16. She went on to become a teacher at a country school in Custer County,Neb., when she was 18. Many of the 35 pupils she taught were the same age shewas.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MATTIE BELLE JONES, 99, FORMER TEACHER ANDBOOKKEEPER  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Later, Mrs. Jones returned to Fremont Normal School and enrolled in abusiness course. She graduated and worked as a bookkeeper in several hardwarestores, and also was private secretary to the president of theNebraska-Missouri Farmers Union. It was there that she met her future husband,Arthur O. Jones, who was the union's organizer for Missouri. They were marriedin 1927. Mr. Jones died in 1954.;    Mrs. Jones came to California in 1952.She worked for Montgomery Ward in Palo Alto for six years and then in thecredit office at O'Connor Hospital in San Jose for six years before retiringat the age of 74.;    She was a member of St. Mark's Episcopal Church and alongtime member of the Order of Eastern Star in Nebraska and California.;   After retirement, Mrs. Jones remained active. She was an avid bridge playerand spent many of her later years doing genealogical research. She compiled acomplete record of her family's ancestors, tracing them to the founding of theMassachusetts Bay Colony in 1630.;    She is survived by three children, DonnaR. Jones of Cupertino, Joan Sainten of San Francisco and Dr. Noel K. Jones ofWilmington, N.C.; a sister, Emma Todd of Waterloo, Neb.; and fourgrandchildren.;    Tuesday's service will be at 1:30 p.m. at St. Mark'sEpiscopal Church in Santa Clara. In lieu of flowers, the family prefersdonations to a memorial fund established at the church, 1957 Pruneridge Ave.,Santa Clara 95050.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910428  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  7B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  349  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday April 28, 199100119157,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>